Curl the fuzzy wires into the shape of a pig's tail. Drill the other side of the toaster for a screw to fit in, this is where you are going to put the pig's tail. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/40/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet13.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet13.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/4/40/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet13.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet13.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Install the screw. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2d/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet14.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet14.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/2/2d/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet14.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet14.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Make sure you shave off the end of the fuzzy wire just to be sure it won't heat up and potentially catch fire. Once shaved, it should be easy to tie the fuzzy wire to the screw you installed. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/78/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet15.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet15.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/78/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet15.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet15.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Attach the tail to the toaster's body. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/71/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet16.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet16.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/7/71/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet16.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-7Bullet16.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

There are a few ways to approach this:
Place frozen bacon in the toaster oven the night before. On the one hand, the bacon could sit in the toaster oven for a few hours, thaw and be perfect for cooking. However, be absolutely certain that allowing meat to sit out for a long period of time will most likely attract bacteria, causing it to be unsafe for eating. This is especially so if your room is warm. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4c/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/4/4c/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet1.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Set another alarm to wake you up a few minutes before your toaster oven is set to activate. Head to the kitchen refrigerator to grab a few pieces of bacon and place in toaster oven. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/46/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/4/46/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet2.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Keep a small refrigerator near your toaster oven where you will maintain your bacon supply. Set another alarm and when it goes off, simply roll over, remove the bacon and place in toaster oven. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d0/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"/images/thumb/d/d0/Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet3.jpg/aid2745419-v4-728px-Make-a-Bacon-Alarm-Clock-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"485","licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
